        "text": "who delight",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The R.V. gives the true rendering. The Hebrew word is more generally used of ‘delight in’ a person or a thing, e.g. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 19:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 112:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; but it is also found with an infin., e.g. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 40:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘I delight to do thy will, O God.’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 58:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘delight to know my ways.’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 6:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c. ‘the king delighteth to honour.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "‘delight to fear.’ The union of fear and joy is the paradox of spiritual service. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 2:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘Serve the Lord with fear and rejoice with trembling,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 22:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘Ye that fear the Lord praise him.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thy name",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. Thy nature and Thy attributes. As often in the O. T. For ‘fear thy name,’ comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 86:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Malachi 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "this ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The same word as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘at this time,’ and to be understood here in the same sense. There is an obvious interval of time between ch. 1. and ch. 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and grant him mercy",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The idiom here employed, literally ‘and give him to mercy’ occurs with the word here used for ‘mercy’ (rachamim = ‘bowels’ or ‘mercies,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὰ σπλάγχνα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The sense strictly is ‘and give him over for purposes, or as an object, of mercy and kindness,’ just as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘give them up to spoiling’ represents an opposite thought.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in the sight of this man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. the king; the final words of the prayer are explained by the parenthetical clause which follows. The word ‘this’ shows that the prayer was the petition of Nehemiah at the king’s court, not necessarily in his presence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For I was",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c.] R.V. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Now I was",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.) The clause in the Hebrew is parenthetical.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the king’s cupbearer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "cupbearer to the king.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The article is wanting before ‘cupbearer.’ Nehemiah stood in the relation of ‘cupbearer’ to the Persian king, but there were others holding the same office. Compare the use of the plural, ‘cupbearers,’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the title of ‘chief butler,’ i.e. chief of the cupbearer, in Genesis 40, 41; and the title Rab-shakeh (= chief cupbearer) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This last passage shows the important place occupied at the court by the head of these functionaries. For, although the title probably represents the Assyrian ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rab-sak",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’ = ‘Generalissimo,’ the Hebrew transliteration of it, based on the similarity of sound conveyed the idea of ‘chief cupbearer’ to Hebrew readers, and presupposed his prominence among the ministers of an Oriental king.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A good representation of the duties of a ‘cupbearer’ at the Persian court is given by Xenophon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Cyrop.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " i. 3, 4). See note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The majority of such attendants at an Oriental court were eunuchs. We must certainly admit the probability that the Jews who occupied places of distinction at the court like Nehemiah, Daniel and his companions (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Mordecai (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Esther 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.), Zerubbabel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Es 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Es 4:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), belonged to this class. The words of consolation addressed by the Prophet of the Exile (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 56:4-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to pious Jews, who according to the strict letter of the law were excommunicate, were applicable to such cases.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἰνοχόος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": Vulg. pincerna. The old Rabbinic explanation of the word ‘Tirshatha,’ as equivalent to ‘cupbearer’ and therefore applied to Nehemiah, is an illustration of obsolete methods of derivation (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 2:63",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Prosper thy servant this day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"This day\" does not perhaps mean more than \"at this time\"- in connection with this matter which is now in my thoughts. And grant him mercy in the sight of this man. \"This man\" is, of course, Artaxerxes, though as yet he has not been named. Nehemiah's thoughts have far outstripped his words. He has made up his mind that, in order to remove the reproach of Jerusalem, he must go there in person; that, to do so, he must obtain the king's permission; and that, to get his permission, he needs to be in very special favour with him. All depending on one man only, he has one man only in his mind, who becomes to him, therefore, \"this man.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I was the king's cupbearer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally, \"I was cupbearer to the king.\" Not his sole cupbearer, but one of many. He mentions the fact here, partly to explain the meaning of \"this man\" to the reader, partly because it was his office which would give him access to Artaxerxes, and enable him to profit by the royal \"mercy\" or favour. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Nehemiah 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The prayer closes with the reiterated entreaty that God would hearken to the prayer of His servant (i.e., Nehemiah), and to the prayer of His servants who delight to fear His name (יראה, infin. like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and elsewhere), i.e., of all Israelites who, like Nehemiah, prayed to God to redeem Israel from all his troubles. For himself in particular, Nehemiah also request: \"Prosper Thy servant to-day (היּום like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; לעבדּך may be either the accusative of the person, like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 26:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or the dative: Prosper his design unto Thy servant, like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and give him to mercy (i.e., cause him to find mercy; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") before the face of this man.\" What man he means is explained by the following supplementary remark, \"And I was cup-bearer to the king,\" without whose favour and permission Nehemiah could not have carried his project into execution (as related in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]